        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>silver halide [300130942], silver compounds [300127427], silver, silver compounds, alloys [300241467], nonferrous metal [300011014], metal by composition or origin [300010901], metal [300010900], inorganic material [300010360], materials by composition [300212963], materials (substances) [300010358], Materials (hierarchy name) [300010357], Materials Facet [300264091]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>A pale-yellow, water-insoluble powder, AgI, which darken upon exposure to light, produced by the reaction of silver nitrate with an iodide. It was used chiefly in the manufacture of photographic emulsions from about 1875-1880.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000046682/Random House Dictionary of the English Language (1987)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Polvo amarillo pálido insoluble en agua, AgI, y que se oscurece al exponerse a la luz, por reacción del nitrato de plata con un yoduro. Se utilizó fundamentalmente en la fabricación de emulsiones fotográficas a partir de aproximadamente 1875-1880.
</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Een lichtgeel en onoplosbaar poeder, AgI, dat donker wordt als het aan licht wordt blootgesteld. Het ontstaat door de reactie van zilvernitraat met een jodide. Het werd vanaf 1875-1880 voornamelijk gebruikt bij de productie van fotografische emulsies.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052381/Van Dale Engels-Nederlands (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>化學式為AgI的淡黃色、不溶於水的粉末，由硝酸銀和碘化物相互作用而成，暴露於光下顏色會變深。西元1875年至1880年起，主要用於製造感光乳劑。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
